[Student "S"]
{Partner's 4\D bid is a Splinter Bid. It shows opening hand strength, at least 4-card \S support, and a singleton or void in \Ds.  

Normally you would not ask for Key-Cards with this \D holding. But since you know partner has at most a singleton, and that it is not the singleton \DA, you are safe to do so. You say 4NT, partner replies 6\D. What next? 

WOW! Partner has one Key-Card and a \D void. So the Key-Card is the \SA. You don't know what the rest of partner's hand is, but he can surely take care of that small \C. You bid 7\S.}

